{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778247342,"nonce":"rpU3jVO7ahHCA3SBIF3hffXrhhs=","message":"## Investigation: the implementational gap was the B_w *dimension*, not (a)/(b) flavor\n\nThe xfailed `test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation` (Δv = −0.04% on C\u0026S regime + Eq 15 Q,R) was diagnosed in earlier comments as evidence that production Riccati's B_w is \"flavor-(a) additive force\" while C\u0026S use \"flavor-(b) ΔA·x model-class\". That framing was a misdiagnosis. After re-reading C\u0026S §Model carefully:\n\n- C\u0026S Eq 7 (`ẋ = (A + ΔA)x + Bu`) introduces ΔA as the *physical motivation* for considering arbitrary state-additive disturbances.\n- C\u0026S Eq 9 (`dx = [Ax+Bu]dt + ΔAx dt + Cdw`) lumps the multiplicative ΔA·x and the additive noise Cdw into a single disturbance signal.\n- C\u0026S Eq 13 (`x_{t+1} = A_d x_t + B_d u_t + ε_t`) is the *discrete-time* equation actually used to design the H∞ Riccati. **ε_t ∈ R^n, one component per state coord** — i.e. **B_w = I_n** in the Riccati. The H∞ controller sees a free additive disturbance on every state component, not a state-coupled ΔA·x.\n- C\u0026S Eq 11 then defines the disturbance penalty `J(x,u,ε) = J(x,u) − γ²ε^Tε` — a free-ε flavor-(a) cost in our framing.\n\nSo **C\u0026S's H∞ Riccati IS what we'd call flavor-(a)**: free additive ε with γ² disturbance penalty. The gap is not (a) vs (b); it's the *dimension* of B_w within flavor-(a). The rlrmp default sets B_w to a 2D velocity-force channel (matching the physical curl-field intervenor — `feedbax.intervene.CurlField`), while C\u0026S's H∞ Riccati design uses 6D full-state B_w = I_6.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdded `disturbance_channel` keyword to `linearize_pointmass(...)`, accepting:\n- `\"velocity_force\"` (default, unchanged behaviour) — 2D B_w on velocity row, matches the physical curl-field intervenor.\n- `\"full_state\"` — B_w_d = I_n directly, matches C\u0026S Eq 13's lumped ε.\n\nPlus convenience `cs_faithful_pointmass()` with C\u0026S parameter defaults (mass=1, k=0.1, τ=0.06, dt=0.01) and `disturbance_channel=\"full_state\"`.\n\n## Headline numbers (C\u0026S regime, faithful Eq 15 Q,R, α₁=1, n_steps=80, 15 cm reach)\n\n| B_w channel | γ* | Δv at γ_factor=1.5 | Δv at 1.05·γ* | Δv at 1.001·γ* |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| velocity-force (2D)   | 5.898    | −0.039%  | −0.055% | — |\n| full-state (I_6)      | 11065.82 | **+1.00%** | **+2.12%** | **+2.35%** |\n\nΔv \u003e 0 on C\u0026S regime is now reproducible from clean Riccati rollouts (no need for averaging over perturbed channels). The +2.35% near boundary is in the right ballpark for C\u0026S Fig 1e (which visually shows few-% peak forward velocity shift; their headline \"15% cost increase\" is an integrated cost metric, not Δv).\n\nΔv grows monotonically as γ → γ*, matching the structural property of H∞.\n\n## Sweeps confirming load-bearing variable is the channel, not other secondaries\n\nα₁ sweep (γ_factor=1.5, full-state B_w):\n- α₁=0.1: Δv=+3.07% / α₁=0.3: +1.84% / α₁=1.0: +1.00% / α₁=3.0: +0.58% / α₁=10.0: +0.31%\n\nn_steps sweep (γ_factor=1.5, full-state B_w):\n- 60: +2.24% / 80: +1.00% / 100: +0.52% / 120: +0.31%\n\nα₁ and n_steps shift magnitude but never flip the sign. **Only the B_w channel is sign-determining**: velocity-force gives Δv ≤ 0 across all reasonable α₁/n_steps; full-state gives Δv \u003e 0 across all reasonable α₁/n_steps.\n\n## rlrmp regime under full-state B_w\n\nSame C\u0026S Q,R + cs_faithful B_w, k=10 instead of k=0.1, 50 cm reach:\n- factor=1.05: Δv=+3.27% / 1.20: +2.45% / 1.50: +1.53% / 2.00: +0.85%\n\nSo the C\u0026S signature Δv \u003e 0 is reachable on our canonical k=10 plant too under full-state B_w. The previously-reported +10.8% on rlrmp regime in Part 2.5 used the rlrmp Q,R + velocity-force B_w combo on the rlrmp regime — a *different* H∞ design (looser disturbance attenuation, easier to gain-inflate). Both are positive; magnitudes reflect different design choices.\n\n## Tests\n\n- `test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation` — un-xfailed; now passes (asserts Δv \u003e 0, magnitude in [0.3, 5.0]%).\n- `test_cs_faithful_velocity_inflation_grows_toward_boundary` — new; confirms monotone Δv growth as γ → γ*.\n- `test_cs_disturbance_channel_flips_dv_sign` — new regression guard for the contrast.\n- `test_full_state_disturbance_channel_shape` — new; verifies B_w = I_n on 4-state and 6-state plants.\n- `test_cs_faithful_pointmass_defaults` — new; pins C\u0026S parameter defaults.\n- `test_input_validation` — extended to reject bogus `disturbance_channel`.\n\nFull test suite: 117 passed, 1 xfail (the existing `test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation_flavor_b` S-procedure xfail — its negative result is correct *for that formulation*; see below).\n\n## What this does NOT change\n\nThe §7.2 S-procedure flavor-(b) work (Δv stays ≤ 0 as η grows on C\u0026S regime, mechanism: Q-augmentation damps controller) is still **correct as a statement about that specific formulation** — it tells you that quadratic-stability robustness against ΔA-Frobenius perturbation is not the path to C\u0026S Δv reproduction. That's a separate theoretical result. The training-side flavor-(a) ⊊ (b) thesis is also a separate question that this work doesn't speak to.\n\nThe H∞ Riccati teacher distillation (issue `db35426`) and the induced-gain analyser comparison should now use `cs_faithful_pointmass()` for C\u0026S-regime evaluations and the `\"velocity_force\"` channel for matching the trained controllers' curl-field training environment.\n\n## Branch\n\n`feature/cs-faithful-riccati-investigation`. Commit `0c160e9`. Tests pass locally (117 / 1 xfail).","files":null}]}